<doc id="145661" wikidata="Q190629" url="?curid=145661" title="Centralizer and normalizer">
<text>In mathematics, especially group theory, the centralizer (also called commutant) of a subset &quot;S&quot; in a group &quot;G&quot; is the set formula_1 of elements of &quot;G&quot; that commute with every element of &quot;S&quot;, or equivalently, the set of elements formula_2 such that conjugation by formula_3 leaves each element of &quot;S&quot; fixed. The normalizer of &quot;S&quot; in &quot;G&quot; is the set of elements formula_4 of &quot;G&quot; that satisfy the weaker condition of leaving the set formula_5 fixed under conjugation. The centralizer and normalizer of &quot;S&quot; are subgroups of &quot;G&quot;. Many techniques in group theory are based on studying the centralizers and normalizers of suitable subsets &quot;S&quot;.

Suitably formulated, the definitions also apply to semigroups.

In ring theory, the centralizer of a subset of a [[ring (mathematics)|ring]] is defined with respect to the multiplication of the ring (a semigroup operation). The centralizer of a subset of a ring &quot;R&quot; is a subring of &quot;R&quot;. This article also deals with centralizers and normalizers in a Lie algebra.

The idealizer in a semigroup or ring is another construction that is in the same vein as the centralizer and normalizer.

==Definitions==
===Group and semigroup===
The centralizer of a subset &quot;S&quot; of group (or semigroup) &quot;G&quot; is defined as

:formula_6

where only the first definition applies to semigroups.
If there is no ambiguity about the group in question, the &quot;G&quot; can be suppressed from the notation. When &quot;S&quot; = {&quot;a&quot;} is a singleton set, we write C&quot;G&quot;(&quot;a&quot;) instead of C&quot;G&quot;({&quot;a&quot;}). Another less common notation for the centralizer is Z(&quot;a&quot;), which parallels the notation for the center. With this latter notation, one must be careful to avoid confusion between the center of a group &quot;G&quot;, Z(&quot;G&quot;), and the &quot;centralizer&quot; of an &quot;element&quot; &quot;g&quot; in &quot;G&quot;, Z(&quot;g&quot;).

The normalizer of &quot;S&quot; in the group (or semigroup) &quot;G&quot; is defined as

:formula_7

where again only the first definition applies to semigroups. If the set formula_8 is a subgroup of formula_9, then the normalizer formula_10 is the largest subgroup formula_11 where formula_8 is a normal subgroup of formula_13. The definitions of &quot;centralizer&quot; and &quot;normalizer&quot; are similar but not identical. If &quot;g&quot; is in the centralizer of &quot;S&quot; and &quot;s&quot; is in &quot;S&quot;, then it must be that , but if &quot;g&quot; is in the normalizer, then for some &quot;t&quot; in &quot;S&quot;, with &quot;t&quot; possibly different from &quot;s&quot;. That is, elements of the centralizer of &quot;S&quot; must commute pointwise with &quot;S&quot;, but elements of the normalizer of &quot;S&quot; need only commute with &quot;S as a set&quot;. The same notational conventions mentioned above for centralizers also apply to normalizers. The normalizer should not be confused with the normal closure.

Clearly formula_14 and both are subgroups of formula_9.

===Ring, algebra over a field, Lie ring, and Lie algebra===
If &quot;R&quot; is a ring or an algebra over a field, and &quot;S&quot; is a subset of &quot;R&quot;, then the centralizer of &quot;S&quot; is exactly as defined for groups, with &quot;R&quot; in the place of &quot;G&quot;.

If formula_16 is a Lie algebra (or Lie ring) with Lie product [&quot;x&quot;, &quot;y&quot;], then the centralizer of a subset &quot;S&quot; of formula_16 is defined to be

:formula_18
The definition of centralizers for Lie rings is linked to the definition for rings in the following way. If &quot;R&quot; is an associative ring, then &quot;R&quot; can be given the bracket product . Of course then if and only if . If we denote the set &quot;R&quot; with the bracket product as L&quot;R&quot;, then clearly the &quot;ring centralizer&quot; of &quot;S&quot; in &quot;R&quot; is equal to the &quot;Lie ring centralizer&quot; of &quot;S&quot; in L&quot;R&quot;.

The normalizer of a subset &quot;S&quot; of a Lie algebra (or Lie ring) formula_16 is given by
:formula_20
While this is the standard usage of the term &quot;normalizer&quot; in Lie algebra, this construction is actually the idealizer of the set &quot;S&quot; in formula_16. If &quot;S&quot; is an additive subgroup of formula_16, then formula_23 is the largest Lie subring (or Lie subalgebra, as the case may be) in which &quot;S&quot; is a Lie ideal.

==Example==
Consider the group 
:formula_24 (the symmetric group of permutations of 3 elements).

Take a subset H of the group G: 

:formula_25

Note that [1, 2, 3] is the identity permutation in G and retains the order of each element and [1, 3, 2] is the permutation that fixes the first element and swaps the second and third element.

The normalizer of H with respect to the group G are all elements of G that yield the set H (potentially permuted) when the element conjugates H.
Working out the example for each element of G:

:formula_26 when applied to formula_27: formula_28; therefore [1, 2, 3] is in the Normalizer(H) with respect to G.
:formula_29 when applied to formula_27: formula_28; therefore [1, 3, 2] is in the Normalizer(H) with respect to G.
:formula_32 when applied to formula_27: formula_34; therefore [2, 1, 3] is not in the Normalizer(H) with respect to G.
:formula_35 when applied to formula_27: formula_37; therefore [2, 3, 1] is not in the Normalizer(H) with respect to G.
:formula_38 when applied to formula_27: formula_34; therefore [3, 1, 2] is not in the Normalizer(H) with respect to G.
:formula_41 when applied to formula_27: formula_37; therefore [3, 2, 1] is not in the Normalizer(H) with respect to G.

Therefore, the Normalizer(H) with respect to G is formula_44 since both these group elements preserve the set H under conjugation.

The centralizer of the group G is the set of elements that leave each element of H unchanged by conjugation; that is, the set of elements that commutes with every element in H. 
It&#x27;s clear in this example that the only such element in S3 is H itself ([1, 2, 3], [1, 3, 2]).

==Properties==
===Semigroups===
Let formula_45 denote the centralizer of formula_8 in the semigroup formula_47; i.e. formula_48 Then formula_45 forms a subsemigroup and formula_50; i.e. a commutant is its own bicommutant.

===Groups===
Source:
* The centralizer and normalizer of &quot;S&quot; are both subgroups of &quot;G&quot;.
* Clearly, . In fact, C&quot;G&quot;(&quot;S&quot;) is always a normal subgroup of N&quot;G&quot;(&quot;S&quot;), being the kernel of the homomorphism and the group N&quot;G&quot;(&quot;S&quot;)/C&quot;G&quot;(&quot;S&quot;) acts by conjugation as a group of bijections on &quot;S&quot;. E.g. the Weyl group of a compact Lie group &quot;G&quot; with a torus &quot;T&quot; is defined as , and especially if the torus is maximal (i.e. it is a central tool in the theory of Lie groups. 
* C&quot;G&quot;(C&quot;G&quot;(&quot;S&quot;)) contains &quot;S&quot;, but C&quot;G&quot;(&quot;S&quot;) need not contain &quot;S&quot;. Containment occurs exactly when &quot;S&quot; is abelian.
* If &quot;H&quot; is a subgroup of &quot;G&quot;, then N&quot;G&quot;(&quot;H&quot;) contains &quot;H&quot;.
* If &quot;H&quot; is a subgroup of &quot;G&quot;, then the largest subgroup of &quot;G&quot; in which &quot;H&quot; is normal is the subgroup N&quot;G&quot;(H).
* If &quot;S&quot; is a subset of &quot;G&quot; such that all elements of &quot;S&quot; commute with each other, then the largest subgroup of &quot;G&quot; whose center contains &quot;S&quot; is the subgroup C&quot;G&quot;(S).
* A subgroup &quot;H&quot; of a group &quot;G&quot; is called a of &quot;G&quot; if .
* The center of &quot;G&quot; is exactly C&quot;G&quot;(G) and &quot;G&quot; is an abelian group if and only if .
* For singleton sets, .
* By symmetry, if &quot;S&quot; and &quot;T&quot; are two subsets of &quot;G&quot;, if and only if .
* For a subgroup &quot;H&quot; of group &quot;G&quot;, the N/C theorem states that the factor group N&quot;G&quot;(&quot;H&quot;)/C&quot;G&quot;(&quot;H&quot;) is isomorphic to a subgroup of Aut(&quot;H&quot;), the group of automorphisms of &quot;H&quot;. Since and , the N/C theorem also implies that &quot;G&quot;/Z(&quot;G&quot;) is isomorphic to Inn(&quot;G&quot;), the subgroup of Aut(&quot;G&quot;) consisting of all inner automorphisms of &quot;G&quot;.
* If we define a group homomorphism by , then we can describe N&quot;G&quot;(&quot;S&quot;) and C&quot;G&quot;(&quot;S&quot;) in terms of the group action of Inn(&quot;G&quot;) on &quot;G&quot;: the stabilizer of &quot;S&quot; in Inn(&quot;G&quot;) is &quot;T&quot;(N&quot;G&quot;(&quot;S&quot;)), and the subgroup of Inn(&quot;G&quot;) fixing &quot;S&quot; pointwise is &quot;T&quot;(C&quot;G&quot;(&quot;S&quot;)).
