:formula_15

where formula_16 is the effective volumetric thermal expansion coefficient, and &quot;h0&quot; is the mid-ocean ridge height (compared to some reference).

The assumption that &quot;v&quot; is relatively large is equivalent to the assumption that the thermal diffusivity formula_6 is small compared to formula_18, where &quot;L&quot; is the ocean width (from mid-ocean ridges to continental shelf) and &quot;A&quot; is the age of the ocean basin.

The effective thermal expansion coefficient formula_16 is different from the usual thermal expansion coefficient formula_20 due to isostasic effect of the change in water column height above the lithosphere as it expands or retracts. Both coefficients are related by:

:formula_21

where formula_22 is the rock density and formula_23 is the density of water.

By substituting the parameters by their rough estimates:

:formula_24

gives:

:formula_25

where the height is in meters and time is in millions of years. To get the dependence on &quot;x&quot;, one must substitute &quot;t&quot; = &quot;x&quot;/&quot;v&quot; ~ &quot;Ax&quot;/&quot;L&quot;, where &quot;L&quot; is the distance between the ridge to the continental shelf (roughly half the ocean width), and &quot;A&quot; is the ocean basin age.

Rather than height of the ocean floor formula_26 above a base or reference level formula_27, the depth of the ocean formula_28 is of interest. Because formula_29(with formula_27 measured from the ocean surface):

:formula_31; for the eastern Pacific for example, where formula_32 is the depth at the ridge crest, typically 2600 m.

===Cooling plate model===

The depth predicted by the square root of seafloor age derived above is too deep for seafloor older than 80 million years. Depth is better explained by a cooling lithosphere plate model rather than the cooling mantle half-space. The plate has a constant temperature at its base and spreading edge. Analysis of depth versus age and depth versus square root of age data allowed Parsons and Sclater to estimate model parameters (for the North Pacific):

:~125 km for lithosphere thickness
:formula_33 at base and young edge of plate
:formula_34

Assuming isostatic equilibrium everywhere beneath the cooling plate yields a revised age depth relationship for older sea floor that is approximately correct for ages as young as 20 million years:

:formula_35 meters

Thus older seafloor deepens more slowly than younger and in fact can be assumed almost constant at ~6400 m depth. Parsons and Sclater concluded that some style of mantle convection must apply heat to the base of the plate everywhere to prevent cooling down below 125 km and lithosphere contraction (seafloor deepening) at older ages. Their plate model also allowed an expression for conductive heat flow, &quot;q(t)&quot; from the ocean floor, which is approximately constant at formula_36 beyond 120 million years:

:formula_37

